Here's how to implement this in .NET MAUI Shell:

**EditProductPage.xaml**
```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="YourApp.EditProductPage"
             Shell.BackButtonBehavior="{StaticResource CancelBackButton}">

    <ContentPage.Resources>
        <BackButtonBehavior x:Key="CancelBackButton"
                            TextOverride="Cancel"
                            Command="{Binding BackCommand}" />
    </ContentPage.Resources>

    <!-- your form here -->
</ContentPage>
```

**EditProductPage.xaml.cs**
```csharp
public partial class EditProductPage : ContentPage
{
    private bool _hasUnsavedChanges;

    public EditProductPage()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        BindingContext = this;
        BackCommand = new Command(OnBackRequested);
    }

    public ICommand BackCommand { get; }

    // Intercept hardware/gesture back navigation
    protected override bool OnBackButtonPressed()
    {
        if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            ShowUnsavedChangesDialog();
            return true; // cancel navigation
        }
        return base.OnBackButtonPressed(); // allow navigation
    }

    private async void OnBackRequested()
    {
        if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            await ShowUnsavedChangesDialog();
        }
        else
        {
            await Shell.Current.GoBackAsync();
        }
    }

    private async Task ShowUnsavedChangesDialog()
    {
        bool leave = await DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (leave)
            await Shell.Current.GoBackAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

- `Shell.BackButtonBehavior` with `TextOverride="Cancel"` replaces the back arrow with a "Cancel" label and routes taps through your command.
- `OnBackButtonPressed()` intercepts the Android hardware/gesture back — return `true` to cancel.
- On iOS, the Shell back button behavior's `Command` handles the nav bar button; swipe-back can be disabled if needed via a platform-specific renderer.

> ⚠️ iOS swipe-back gesture bypasses `OnBackButtonPressed`. To block it, disable it on the navigation controller in a custom handler or set `IsEnabled="False"` on `BackButtonBehavior` conditionally.
